docs.abstract: The United States is casting Cuba and Russia as enablers to President Nicolás Maduro, and penalized a Moscow bank accused of helping his government evade American sanctions.
docs.snippet: The United States is casting Cuba and Russia as enablers to President Nicolás Maduro, and penalized a Moscow bank accused of helping his government evade American sanctions.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Secretary of State Mike Pompeo accused Cuba and Russia on Monday of propping up President Nicolás Maduro of Venezuela in the Trump administration’s most explicit argument yet that his government is a dictatorial regime kept alive by two American adversaries.

headline.main: Pompeo Accuses Cuba and Russia of Propping Up Venezuelan Ruler
headline.print_headline: Cuba and Russia Are Propping Up Venezuelan Ruler, Pompeo Says

byline.original: By David E. Sanger, Anatoly Kurmanaev and Isayen Herrera

docs.abstract: Representative Jerrold Nadler, the chairman of the House Judiciary Committee, said it was “very clear that the president obstructed justice.”
docs.snippet: Representative Jerrold Nadler, the chairman of the House Judiciary Committee, said it was “very clear that the president obstructed justice.”
docs.lead_paragraph: Representative Jerrold Nadler, the chairman of the House Judiciary Committee, said Sunday that he planned to request documents from more than 60 people with ties to President Trump, his administration and his businesses, including the president’s eldest son, Donald Trump Jr., as part of the committee’s investigation of the president.

headline.main: Key House Democrat Plans to Request Documents From Dozens of People Tied to Trump
headline.print_headline: House Democrat to Seek Documents From Trump Contacts

byline.original: By Glenn Thrush and Nicholas Fandos

docs.abstract: The House voted Wednesday to require background checks for all gun purchasers, the first major expansion of gun control laws in over two decades.
docs.snippet: The House voted Wednesday to require background checks for all gun purchasers, the first major expansion of gun control laws in over two decades.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The House voted on Wednesday to require background checks for all gun purchasers, including those at gun shows and on the internet — the first significant gun control bill to clear the chamber in a quarter of a century.

headline.main: House Passes First Major Gun Control Law in Decades
headline.print_headline: House Passes First Major Gun Control Law in Decades

docs.lead_paragraph: PALM BEACH, Fla. — President Trump’s pick to serve as ambassador to the United Nations withdrew from consideration on Saturday, citing family concerns.

headline.print_headline: Ex-Fox Host Quits Effort To Be Named U.N. Envoy

byline.original: By Annie Karni and Maggie Haberman

docs.abstract: When it comes to congressional end runs, lawmakers warn President Trump that what goes around comes around.
docs.snippet: When it comes to congressional end runs, lawmakers warn President Trump that what goes around comes around.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Outraged House Republicans sued President Barack Obama in 2014 for spending billions of federal dollars without congressional approval — and won. Now many House and Senate Republicans could side with President Trump for doing what they saw as a grave abuse of power by Mr. Obama — circumventing an unwilling Congress in a spending dispute.

headline.main: In Wielding Emergency Powers, Trump Paves a Dangerous Path Forward
headline.print_headline: Laying Out a Dangerous Path Forward

docs.abstract: Michael T. Flynn, the president’s former national security adviser, had cooperated with the special counsel, but in asking for leniency, he stoked an unfounded theory about potential evidence he did not lie to investigators.
docs.snippet: Michael T. Flynn, the president’s former national security adviser, had cooperated with the special counsel, but in asking for leniency, he stoked an unfounded theory about potential evidence he did not lie to investigators.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The special counsel’s office rejected on Friday a suggestion from Michael T. Flynn, President Trump’s former national security adviser, that he had been tricked into lying last year to F.B.I. agents investigating Russia’s election interference and ties to Trump associates.

headline.main: Mueller Rejects Flynn’s Attempt to Portray Himself as Victim of the F.B.I.
headline.print_headline: Mueller Shuns Idea That Flynn Was Duped Into Lying to F.B.I.

docs.abstract: Ms. Conway, a counselor to President Trump, falsely claimed that he did not know about payments to two women until this year, and misleadingly suggested the arrangement occurred in August 2015.
docs.snippet: Ms. Conway, a counselor to President Trump, falsely claimed that he did not know about payments to two women until this year, and misleadingly suggested the arrangement occurred in August 2015.
docs.lead_paragraph: Mr. Cohen, Mr. Trump’s former personal lawyer, pleaded guilty in August to breaking campaign finance laws when he arranged payments to two women during the 2016 presidential campaign to keep them from talking about affairs they said they had with Mr. Trump.

headline.main: Kellyanne Conway’s Inaccurate Claims About Michael Cohen’s Hush-Money Payments

docs.abstract: At an extraordinary hearing that gripped the country, Dr. Blasey emotionally detailed the night she said Judge Brett M. Kavanaugh sexually assaulted her.
docs.snippet: At an extraordinary hearing that gripped the country, Dr. Blasey emotionally detailed the night she said Judge Brett M. Kavanaugh sexually assaulted her.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Judge Brett M. Kavanaugh and his accuser faced off Thursday in an extraordinary, emotional day of testimony that ricocheted from a woman’s tremulous account of sexual assault to a man’s angry, outraged denial, all of which played out for hours before a riveted nation and a riven Senate.

headline.main: Brett Kavanaugh and Christine Blasey Ford Duel With Tears and Fury
headline.print_headline: High-Stakes Duel of Tears and Fury Unfold In Senate

byline.original: By Sheryl Gay Stolberg and Nicholas Fandos

docs.abstract: Under the new regulation, which had been expected, Americans who own bump stocks would have 90 days to destroy their devices or to turn them over to the A.T.F.
docs.snippet: Under the new regulation, which had been expected, Americans who own bump stocks would have 90 days to destroy their devices or to turn them over to the A.T.F.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Trump administration on Tuesday issued a new rule banning bump stocks, the attachments that enable semiautomatic rifles to fire in sustained, rapid bursts and that a gunman used to massacre 58 people and wound hundreds of others at a Las Vegas concert in October 2017.

headline.main: Trump Administration Imposes Ban on Bump Stocks
headline.print_headline: U.S. Issues Regulation To Prohibit Bump Stocks

docs.abstract: After the Senate passed a spending measure, conservative anger pushed President Trump to torpedo it, leaving Republican leaders scrambling for a way out of the morass.
docs.snippet: After the Senate passed a spending measure, conservative anger pushed President Trump to torpedo it, leaving Republican leaders scrambling for a way out of the morass.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump on Thursday torpedoed a spending deal and sent the government careening toward a Christmastime shutdown over his demand of $5 billion for a wall on the southwestern border, refusing to sign a stopgap measure to keep funds flowing past midnight Friday.

headline.main: Demanding Wall Funding, Trump Balks at Bill to Avert Shutdown

byline.original: By Julie Hirschfeld Davis and Emily Cochrane
